1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 HOUSE BILL 2982 By: Banning
4
5
6 AS INTRODUCED
7 An Act relating to the Oklahoma Higher Learning
Access Program; amending 70 O.S. 2021, Section 2605,
8 as last amended by Section 2, Chapter 485, O.S.L.
2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 2605), which
9 relates to student agreements; expanding eligibility
of program to children of certified classroom
10 teachers who graduated during the 2024-2025 school
year; and declaring an emergency.
11
12
13 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
14 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 2605, as
15 last amended by Section 2, Chapter 485, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp.
16 2025, Section 2605), is amended to read as follows:
17 Section 2605. A. Each school year, every fifth- through
18 eleventh-grade student in the public and private schools of this
19 state and students who are educated by other means and are in the
20 equivalent of the fifth through eleventh grade shall be apprised,
21 together with the parent, custodial parent, or guardian of the
22 student, of the opportunity for access to higher learning under the
23 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program. The Oklahoma State Regents
24 for Higher Education and the State Board of Education shall develop,
Req. No. 14152 Page 1

1 prom ote, and coordinate a public awareness program to be utilized in
2 making students and parents aware of the Oklahoma Higher Learning
3 Access Program.
4 B. On a form provided by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
5 Education, every public school district shall designate at least one
6 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program contact person, who shall be
7 a counselor or teacher, at each public school site in this state in
8 which eighth-, ninth-, tenth-, or eleventh-grade classes are taught.
9 When requested by the State Regents, the State Board of Education
10 shall assist the State Regents to ensure the designation of contact
11 persons. Private schools shall also designate at least one school
12 official as a contact person. For students who are educated by
13 other means, a parent or guardian or other person approved by the
14 State Regents shall be designated the contact person.
15 C. 1. Students who qualify on the basis of financial need
16 according to subsection D or E of this section or who meet the
17 eligibility qualification set forth in subparagraph a of paragraph 1
18 of subsection B of Section 2603 of this title no later than December
19 31 of their twelfth-grade year or prior to reaching the age of
20 seventeen (17) and who qualify on the basis of the standards and
21 provisions promulgated by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
22 Education shall be given the opportunity throughout the eighth-,
23 ninth-, tenth-, and eleventh-grade years and no later than December
24 31 of the twelfth-grade year, for students enrolled in a public or
Req. No. 14152 Page 2

1 priv ate school, or between the ages of thirteen (13) and seventeen
2 (17), for students who are educated by other means, to enter into
3 participation in the program by agreeing to, throughout the
4 remainder of their school years or educational program:
5 a. attend school or an educational program regularly and
6 do homework regularly,
7 b. refrain from substance abuse,
8 c. refrain from commission of crimes or delinquent acts,
9 d. have school work and school records reviewed by
10 mentors designated pursuant to the program,
11 e. provide information requested by the Oklahoma State
12 Regents for Higher Education or the State Board of
13 Education, and
14 f. participate in program activities.
15 2. Students who meet the eligibility qualification set forth in
16 subparagraph a of paragraph 1 of subsection B of Section 2603 of
17 this title after December 31 of their twelfth-grade year or after
18 reaching the age of eighteen (18) shall be given the opportunity
19 prior to reaching the age of twenty-one (21) to enter into
20 participation in the program and shall execute an agreement with
21 provisions as determined by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
22 Education.
23 3. The contact person shall maintain the agreements, which
24 shall be executed on forms provided by the Oklahoma State Regents
Req. No. 14152 Page 3

1 for Higher Education and managed according to regulations
2 promulgated by the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education, and
3 the contact person shall monitor compliance of the student with the
4 terms of the agreement. The Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
5 Education are authorized to process student agreements and verify
6 compliance with the agreements. Students failing to comply with the
7 terms of the agreement shall not be eligible for the awards provided
8 in Section 2604 of this title.
9 4. The Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education may provide
10 an exception to the age limits provided for in paragraphs 1 and 2 of
11 this subsection pursuant to subsection L of this section.
12 5. Notwithstanding the provisions of Sections 5-132 and 5-132.1
13 of this title, a student who is age twenty-one (21) or older shall
14 not be eligible to enter into participation in the program.
15 D. Except as otherwise provided for in subsection E of this
16 section and except for students who qualify pursuant to subsection B
17 of Section 2603 of this title, a student shall not be found to be in
18 financial need for purposes of the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access
19 Program if:
20 1. Beginning with eighth-, ninth-, or tenth-grade students who
21 are enrolled in a public or private school or students between the
22 ages of thirteen (13) and fifteen (15) who are educated by other
23 means who apply for participation in the program in the 2017-2018
24
Req. No. 14152 Page 4

1 scho ol year, the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
2 parent(s) exceeds Fifty-five Thousand Dollars ($55,000.00) per year;
3 2. Beginning with eighth-, ninth-, tenth-, or eleventh-grade
4 students who are enrolled in a public or private school or students
5 between the ages of thirteen (13) and sixteen (16) who are educated
6 by other means who apply for participation in the program in the
7 2021-2022 school year, the federal adjusted gross income of the
8 student's parent(s) exceeds Sixty Thousand Dollars ($60,000.00) per
9 year;
10 3. Beginning with eighth-, ninth-, tenth-, or eleventh-grade
11 students who are enrolled in a public or private school or students
12 between the ages of thirteen (13) and sixteen (16) who are educated
13 by other means who apply for participation in the program in the
14 2022-2023 school year:
15 a. the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
16 parent(s), who have two or fewer dependent children,
17 exceeds Sixty Thousand Dollars ($60,000.00) per year,
18 b. the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
19 parent(s), who have three or four dependent children,
20 exceeds Seventy Thousand Dollars ($70,000.00) per
21 year, or
22 c. the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
23 parent(s), who have five or more dependent children,
24 exceeds Eighty Thousand Dollars ($80,000.00) per year;
Req. No. 14152 Page 5

1 4. Beginning with eighth-, ninth-, tenth-, or eleventh-grade
2 students or twelfth-grade students no later than December 31 of
3 their twelfth-grade year who are enrolled in a public or private
4 school or students between the ages of thirteen (13) and seventeen
5 (17) who are educated by other means who apply for participation in
6 the program in the 2025-2026 school year:
7 a. the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
8 parent(s), who have two or fewer dependent children,
9 exceeds Sixty Thousand Dollars ($60,000.00) per year,
10 b. the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
11 parent(s), who have three or four dependent children,
12 exceeds Seventy Thousand Dollars ($70,000.00) per
13 year, or
14 c. the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
15 parent(s), who have five or more dependent children,
16 exceeds Eighty Thousand Dollars ($80,000.00) per year;
17 5. Beginning with the 2018-2019 academic year, prior to
18 receiving any Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program benefit award
19 for any year during which the student is enrolled in an institution
20 which is a member of The Oklahoma State System of Higher Education,
21 a postsecondary vocational-technical program offered by a technology
22 center school that meets the requirements to be eligible for federal
23 student financial aid, or a private institution of higher learning
24 located within this state and accredited pursuant to Section 4103 of
Req. No. 14152 Page 6

1 this title, the federal adjusted gross income of the student's
2 parent(s) exceeds One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) per
3 year.
4 The determination of financial qualification as set forth in
5 this paragraph shall be based on the income of the student, not the
6 income of the parent(s), if a student:
7 a. is determined to be independent of the student's
8 parents for federal financial aid purposes,
9 b. was in the permanent custody of the Department of
10 Human Services at the time the student enrolled in the
11 program, or
12 c. was in the court-ordered custody of a federally
13 recognized Indian tribe, as defined by the federal
14 Indian Child Welfare Act of 1978, at the time the
15 student enrolled in the program.
16 The provisions of this paragraph shall apply to any student who
17 has received an Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program benefit
18 award after the 2017-2018 school year; and
19 6. The Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education shall review
20 the determination of financial qualification as set forth in
21 paragraphs 1, 2, 3, and 4 of this subsection if the income from
22 taxable and nontaxable sources of the student's parent(s) includes
23 income received from nontaxable military benefits or income received
24 from the federal Social Security Administration due to the death or
Req. No. 14152 Page 7

1 disa bility of the student's parent(s). If the income from taxable
2 and nontaxable sources of the student's parent(s), excluding income
3 received from nontaxable military benefits or income received from
4 the federal Social Security Administration due to the death or
5 disability of the student's parent(s), does not exceed the
6 limitations set forth by paragraphs 1, 2, 3, and 4 of this
7 subsection, the student shall be determined to have met the
8 financial qualification set forth in paragraphs 1, 2, 3, and 4 of
9 this subsection.
10 E. 1. A student who was adopted between birth and twelve (12)
11 years of age while in the permanent custody of the Department of
12 Human Services, in the court-ordered custody of a licensed private
13 nonprofit child-placing agency, or federally recognized Indian
14 tribe, as defined by the federal Indian Child Welfare Act of 1978,
15 shall not be found to be in financial need for purposes of the
16 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program if at the time the student
17 begins postsecondary education and prior to receiving any Oklahoma
18 Higher Learning Access Program benefit award, the federal adjusted
19 gross income of the student's parent(s) exceeds One Hundred Fifty
20 Thousand Dollars ($150,000.00) per year. The provisions of this
21 paragraph shall not apply to any student who has received an
22 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program benefit award prior to the
23 2012-2013 school year.
24
Req. No. 14152 Page 8

1 2. A student who was adopted between thirteen (13) and
2 seventeen (17) years of age while in the permanent custody of the
3 Department of Human Services, in the court-ordered custody of a
4 licensed private nonprofit child-placing agency, or federally
5 recognized Indian tribe, as defined by the federal Indian Child
6 Welfare Act of 1978, shall not be found to be in financial need for
7 purposes of the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program if at the
8 time the student begins postsecondary education and prior to
9 receiving any Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program benefit award,
10 the federal adjusted gross income of the student's parent(s) exceeds
11 Two Hundred Thousand Dollars ($200,000.00) per year. The provisions
12 of this paragraph shall not apply to any student who has received an
13 Oklahoma Higher Learning Access Program benefit award prior to the
14 2012-2013 school year.
15 3. A student who was placed in the custody of the Department of
16 Human Services at any time during the eighth, ninth, tenth, or
17 eleventh grade and enrolls in the program no later than his or her
18 official date of high school graduation shall not be found to be in
19 financial need for purposes of the Oklahoma Higher Learning Access
20 Program if the federal adjusted gross income of the student exceeds
21 Sixty Thousand Dollars ($60,000.00) per year.
22 4. Except for students who qualify pursuant to subsection B of
23 Section 2603 of this title, the determination of financial
24 qualification as set forth in this subsection shall be based on the
Req. No. 14152 Page 9

